        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Down Bromley Kent</placeName>
                    <date>Aug<hi rend="superscript">t</hi>. 15<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>.—</date>
                    <salute>My dear Lord</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>We are very much obliged for your Lordship’s kind invitation to dinner on Saturday, but I am sorry to say that my health still prevents me going out to a distance in the evening;—and a very great loss it is to me in this instance.—</p>
<p>With our best thanks, I beg leave to remain | Your Lordships | Truly obliged | Charles Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
             
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The recipient is inferred from the reference to ‘your Lordship’. Rolfe was created Baron Cranworth in 1850. He lived at Holwood House in Keston, Kent, a few miles from Down. See also <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic"> Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 7, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-2357.xml" resp="#automat">letter to R. M. Rolfe, 10 November [1858]</ref>.</note>
        </div>        
            
